\cf0 Observations and Analysis\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The low-temperature output focused on factual information and product specifications with minimal creativity. The medium-temperature output balanced technical details with persuasive language, making it suitable for product listings and online stores. The high-temperature output emphasized storytelling, emotions, and customer benefits, resulting in a more engaging and memorable product description.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb5 2.2 Analysis & Recommendations\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa319\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb1 1. When would you use low temperature? (Give 2 specific use cases)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Use Case 1: Technical Documentation\uc0\u8232 When creating user manuals, API documentation, or software instructions, a low temperature is preferred because it produces consistent, accurate, and predictable responses.\
Use Case 2: Customer Support Responses\uc0\u8232 For answering frequently asked questions or providing standard troubleshooting steps, low temperature ensures reliable and factually correct information without unnecessary variation.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa319\partightenfactor0
\cf0 2. When would you use high temperature? (Give 2 specific use cases)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Use Case 1: Creative Writing\uc0\u8232 When generating stories, poems, or fictional content, a high temperature encourages originality, imagination, and diverse ideas.\
Use Case 2: Marketing and Advertising\uc0\u8232 For creating slogans, taglines, social media campaigns, or brainstorming product names, a high temperature helps produce unique and engaging content that captures attention.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa319\partightenfactor0
\cf0 3. Which temperature worked best for your chosen task and why?\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 For the task of writing a product description for a laptop, the medium temperature (0.7) worked best. It provided a balance between factual product information and persuasive marketing language. Unlike the low temperature, which focused mainly on specifications, and the high temperature, which emphasized creativity over details, the medium temperature produced a professional and engaging description suitable for e-commerce platforms and product marketing.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Part 3: Strategic Prompting Techniques\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Problem:\
Problem: A company has 150 employees. 60% work in engineering, 25% in sales, and the rest in operations. If the company plans to hire 20% more engineers and 10% more sales people, how many total employees will there be after hiring?\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Without Chain-of-Thought\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Prompt\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 A company has 150 employees. 60% work in engineering, 25% in sales, and the rest in operations. If the company plans to hire 20% more engineers and 10% more sales people, how many total employees will there be after hiring? Give only the final answer.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0
\cf0 LLM Output\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 172 employees\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0
\cf0 With Chain-of-Thought\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Prompt\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 A company has 150 employees. 60% work in engineering, 25% in sales, and the rest in operations. If the company plans to hire 20% more engineers and 10% more sales people, how many total employees will there be after hiring? Let's solve this step by step and explain the calculations.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0
\cf0 LLM Output\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls30\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Engineering employees = 60% of 150 = 90\
\ls30\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Sales employees = 25% of 150 = 37.5\
\ls30\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Additional engineers hired = 20% of 90 = 18\
\ls30\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Additional sales employees hired = 10% of 37.5 = 3.75\
\ls30\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	5	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Total new hires = 18 + 3.75 = 21.75\
\ls30\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	6	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Total employees after hiring = 150 + 21.75 = 171.75\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Rounded to the nearest whole employee, the company will have 172 employees after hiring.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Comparison\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The output without chain-of-thought provided only the final answer, making it difficult to understand how the result was obtained. The chain-of-thought version broke the problem into smaller calculations, making the reasoning process transparent and easier to verify. Chain-of-thought prompting helps with complex reasoning because it encourages the model to solve problems in logical steps rather than jumping directly to a conclusion.\
\
